> I'm currently failing to understand which use case requires one to extend the traversable interface.

Any interface whose implementation is supposed to be traversable needs to extend it. A very simple example:

``` php
<?php
interface ArrayInterface extends \ArrayAccess, \Countable, \Traversable {}

// The implementation can chose to implement \Iterator...
class Array1 implements \Iterator, ArrayInterface
{
    ...
}

// or \IteratorAggregate
class Array2 implements \IteratorAggregate, ArrayInterface
{
    ...
}
```

Interfaces usually specify a contract, without specifying _how_ that contract should be implemented. These core interfaces are special in that `\Traversable` specifies the contract ("This object should be iterable") while `\Iterator` and `\IteratorAggregate` specify how that contract is implemented. Consequently, no userland interface should them, but always `\Traversable` IMHO.

issue.body:
Copied from sebastianbergmann/phpunit#604

Currently, PHPUnit fails when trying to mock an interface that implements `\Traversable` because PHP expects implementations of that interface to also either implement `\Iterator` or `\IteratorAggregate`.

``` php
<?php

interface MyInterface extends \Traversable {}

// doesn't work
$this->getMock('MyInterface');
```

The fix currently is to extend the interface for testing purposes and to add one of the two required interfaces (_Note_: The order of the interfaces is important here!)

``` php
<?php

interface TestMyInterface extends \Iterator, MyInterface {}

// works
$this->getMock('TestMyInterface');
```

IMO PHPUnit should be able to add that interface automatically in such situations, i.e.:
- when the mock is created for an interface or an abstract class, and
- that interface/abstract class implements `\Traversable`, but not `\Iterator` nor `\IteratorAggregate`

For reference, see http://webmozarts.com/2012/10/07/give-the-traversable-interface-some-love/.

I have an interface that extends from `\IteratorAggregate`, like so:

```php
interface IDbStatement extends \IteratorAggregate
{
    public function Execute(array $parameters = null);
    public function FetchField(int $index = 0);
    public function FetchFullColumn(int $columnIndex = 0);
}
```

And we know that `\IteratorAggregate` itself extends from `\Traversable`:

```php
/**
 * Interface to create an external Iterator.
 * @link http://php.net/manual/en/class.iteratoraggregate.php
 */
interface IteratorAggregate extends Traversable {

    /**
     * Retrieve an external iterator
     * @link http://php.net/manual/en/iteratoraggregate.getiterator.php
     * @return Traversable An instance of an object implementing <b>Iterator</b> or
     * <b>Traversable</b>
     * @since 5.0.0
     */
    public function getIterator();
}
```

This test succeeds:

```php
public function testMockDbStatementCanBeTraversed()
{
    $mockDbStatement = $this->createMock(IDbStatement::class);
    self::assertInstanceOf(\Traversable::class, $mockDbStatement);
}
```

And this test **throws an exception** with `Objects returned by Mock_IDbStatement_a37ef142::getIterator() must be traversable or implement interface Iterator`:

```php
public function testMockDbStatementCanBeTraversed()
{
    $mockDbStatement = $this->createMock(IDbStatement::class);

    foreach ($mockDbStatement as $item)
    {
        $throwaway = null;
    }

    self::assertInstanceOf(\Traversable::class, $mockDbStatement);
}
```

I've looked at issues #103 and #186, as well as sebastianbergmann/phpunit#604, but can't see anything that applies to this particular situation. I'm at a loss as to _why_ this is failing and would appreciate some insight.

Mocking the `getIterator()` method does not work:

```php
public function testMockDbStatementCanBeTraversed()
{
    $mockDbStatement = $this->createMock(IDbStatement::class);

    $mockDbStatement
        ->method('getIterator')
        ->willReturn($mockDbStatement);

    foreach ($mockDbStatement as $item)
    {
        $throwaway = null;
    }

    self::assertInstanceOf(\Traversable::class, $mockDbStatement);
}
```
